@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
LoadLibs is a small CLI program that can load one or multiple libraries,
datatypes or classes to memory, much like the old ARP LoadLib but much more
advanced.

@{b}Features of LoadLibs@{ub}

    - Can load one or multiple libraries/classes/datatypes.
    - Can force them to be loaded to any memory block.
    - Can prevent libraries from being flushed out from memory.
    - Can list all libraries in memory and some information about them.
    - Can remove a library from memory.
    + some other things mentioned in the manual.
@endnode

@node "WhyToUse" "Why?"
@{b}@{u}Why I wrote it@{ub}@{uu}

I needed a program that could open several libraries and prevent them from
ever being flushed out from the memory. I also wanted a program that could
show in which memory block the library was located and optionally force
libraries to be loaded to a certain memory block.

I used the old @{i}ARP LoadLib@{ui} but that program could only load one library at a
time and had no other features. I had a look at Aminet and found a few similar
programs which in combination with a few other programs made roughly what I
wanted, but I needed/wanted one program to do it all.
@endnode

@node "ReasonsToUse" "Purpose"
@{b}@{u}How the Amiga opens libraries@{ub}@{uu}

Whenever a program needs a certain library, it tries to open it using the
dos.library function OpenLibrary(). If the library is opened for the first
time and does not already exist in the memory, OpenLibrary will try to load
the library from LIBS:

@{b}Great. So what's the problem?@{ub}

Suppose you are still using disk drives, then you probably hate the "insert
volume XXX:" requester whenever the program you're running decides to open a
certain library from the boot disk you no longer have in any drive. You can
use LoadLibs to load all important libraries to memory on startup, to avoid
this problem.

Or suppose you are trying to load the great GameX that needs
"greatgame.library" to be loaded from df0:libs only to be faced with  "can't
find df0:libs/greatgame.library" because you have decided to install it
somewhere else. On your hard disk perhaps. Use LoadLibs to load it to memory
before starting GameX.

Or perhaps you want to try the great BigProgX without installing a lot of
libraries to libs:. One solution is to add an assign to the BigProgX/libs
directory or use a program that patches OpenLibrary to look in progdir:,
current directory etc. But you can also use LoadLibs to load the libraries
before you run BigProgX.

@{b}These are the basic functions of LoadLibs and other similar programs. But
LoadLibs have some more advanced functions that are of more interest today,
when everybody have hard disks and several megs of memory.

If you have several different types of memory, such as 16 bit chipmem, 16 bit
fastmem and 32 bit fastmem you'll probably sometimes end up with libraries
that require speed, such as XPK-libraries, in 16 bit fast or  even chipmem,
and at the same time big libraries that require little speed end up in your
precious 32 bit fastmem. You can use LoadLibs to force these libraries to the
memory block of your choice.

Loading several libraries at a time may reduce memory fragmentation, which can
be nice if you need/want to flush the memory.

LoadLibs can also prevent libraries from being (accidently or not) flushed out
from memory. This will guarantee that the libraries are always where you
expect them to be. I had a problem with XFH/XPK (don't know which to  blame)
that caused a system lock up if I flushed out any xpk-library.  By using the
WAIT/S or NOCLOSE/S option the library is resident in memory even after you
execute "avail flush".@{ub}

I also needed a CLI program that listed the address of the library in memory.
Couldn't find one so I implemented the LIST/S switch.
@endnode

@node "Brief Usage" "Brief usage"
@{b}LoadLibs v1.0 is a CLI-only program and has several options to control the
loading/usage of libraries.@{ub}

Here is a brief description of the different arguments accepted by LoadLibs.
For more info click the appropriate gadget or see the @{"full usage" link "Usage" 0} page.

@{"LIBRARY/M" link "Usage" 14}   :   One or several libraries/classes/datatypes to be loaded.
                The keyword "LIBRARY" is optional.
                The names are @{i}case sensitive@{ui}.

                The default is to load from LIBS: but a full path name
                such as "df0:libs/foo.library" is also legitimate.

@{"TO/K" link "Usage" 69}        :   Forces the library/libraries to be loaded into a certain
                memory region.
                The keyword "TO" is needed and is followed by the name of the
                memory block. Standard wild cards are accepted so chip#?
                matches "chip memory".

@{"LIST/S" link "Usage" 99}      :   Lists all libraries in memory and some information.

@{"REMOVE/S" link "Usage" 113}    :   This switch will try to remove the library/libraries.

@{"WAIT/S" link "Usage" 129}      :   LoadLibs will load the library/libraries and then WAIT for
                a break signal, in this case CTRL-C. It will then close
                the library/libraries and exit.
                @{i}This can be useful if you want to protect your
                library/libraries from being removed.@{ui}

@{"BREAK/S" link "Usage" 146}     :   Sends a break signal to all instances of LoadLibs.

@{"VERSION/S" link "Usage" 157}   :   Checks version number when opening the library/libraries.
                The keyword "VERSION" or "V" is needed.

@{"NOCLOSE/S" link "Usage" 178}   :   LoadLibs doesn't close the library at exit.
                By not closing the library at exit it is protected from
                removal. @{i}It can no longer be removed by "avail flush" or
                "LoadLibs REMOVE" etc.@{ui}

@{"VERBOSE/S" link "Usage" 186}   :   Print some extra information.
                In v1.0 of LoadLibs the extra information is limited to
                the IdString of the library when listing libraries.

@{"QUIET/S" link "Usage" 201}     :   Will suppress output. All errors will still be printed.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Full usage"
@{b}LoadLibs v1.0 is a CLI-only program and has several options to control the
loading/usage of libraries.@{ub}

If you start LoadLibs with "?" as the only argument you will see this:

  @{b}1> LoadLibs ?
  LIBRARY/M,TO/K,LIST/S,REMOVE/S,WAIT/S,BREAK/S,V=VERSION/N,NOCLOSE/S,VERBOSE/
S,Q=QUIET/S:@{ub}

As you can see there are quite a few options and I will try to explain all of
them. Most are pretty self explaining but reading @{"Reasons To Use" link "ReasonsToUse" 0} might be a
good idea if you want some more information about this program.

@{b}LIBRARY/M@{ub}   :   One or several libraries/classes/datatypes to be loaded.

                The keyword "LIBRARY" is optional.

                The names are case sensitive.

                The default is to load from LIBS: but a full path name
                such as "df0:libs/foo.library" is also legitimate.

                Several patches are available to make OpenLibrary look
                for the library not only in LIBS: but also in PROGDIR:,
                PROGDIR:LIBS/ etc.

                The libraries will remain in memory until they are removed
                by either flushing the memory ("c:avail flush") or with
                an external program (remlib, LoadLibs REMOVE etc), or until
                the system decides to remove the libraries to free memory.

                @{i}1> LoadLibs midi.library@{ui}
                [Loads midi.library from LIBS:, closes it and exits.
                 The library remains in memory until it is removed or
                 flushed out.]

                @{i}1> LoadLibs df0:libs/foo.library@{ui}
                [Loads foo.library from df0:libs/ .If foo.library already
                 exists in memory this will succeed even if foo.library
                 doesn't exist on df0:. And that's a feature, not a bug.
                 See [NOTES]]

                LoadLibs can also load classes and datatypes.

                @{i}1> LoadLibs window.class
                window.class v41.4 opened
                Closing window.class
                1>

                1> LoadLibs DH0:Classes/DataTypes/anim.datatype
                DH0:Classes/DataTypes/anim.datatype v40.3 opened
                Closing DH0:Classes/DataTypes/anim.datatype
                1>@{ui}

                And remember, the names are CASE SENSITIVE!

                @{i}1.0-> LoadLibs DH0:Classes/DataTypes/ANIM.datatype
                DH0:Classes/DataTypes/ANIM.datatype error!
                1.5->@{ui}

                -+-

                A previous beta version of LoadLibs supported wild cards
                and also automagically added ".library" to the arguments
                but I removed this because I often accidently loaded stuff
                I didn't want to load and it also made support for datatypes
                and classes more difficult/bad.

@{b}TO/K@{ub}        :   Forces the library/libraries to be loaded into a certain
                memory region.

                This can be very useful if you want to force big libraries
                that are rarely used and don't need speed to use slower
                memory, such as chip-mem or 16-bit fast-mem.

                I use it to force all XPK-libraries to my fast 32-bit memory
                and to force many other libraries to slower 16-bit fast or
                chip memory.

                The keyword "TO" is needed and is followed by the name of the
                memory block.

                @{i}1> LoadLibs ixemul.library TO "chip memory"
                LoadLibs 1.0 (5.9.97) ©1997 Mathias Karlsson
                Loading to 'chip memory'
                ixemul.library v45.1 opened
                Closing ixemul.library
                1>@{ui}

                You can also use standard wild cards to name the memory:

                @{i}1> LoadLibs ixemul.library TO chip#?
                LoadLibs 1.0 (5.9.97) ©1997 Mathias Karlsson
                Loading to 'chip memory'
                ixemul.library v45.1 opened
                Closing ixemul.library
                1>@{ui}

@{b}LIST/S@{ub}      :   Lists all libraries in memory and some information.

                @{i}13.0-> LoadLibs LIST
                LoadLibs 1.0 (5.9.97) ©1997 Mathias Karlsson
                @{b}@{u}Library                VERSION OpenCnt Pri Address@{ub}@{uu}
                screennotify.library     1.0      1     0 $008D871C
                utility.library         40.1     51     0 $002801B0
                ixemul.library          45.1      0     0 $00054E58@{ui}
                (...)

                The address of a library can be interesting to watch.
                On my computer screennotify is in 16-bit fast, utility
                in 32-bit fast and ixemul in chip-mem.

@{b}REMOVE/S@{ub}    :   This switch will try to remove the library/libraries.

                First it will open the library to see that it really
                exists, then it will close the library and call
                dos.library RemLibrary() function that asks the library to
                remove itself. If another program is using the library it
                cannot be removed and nothing will happen.

                Normally, when you are low on memory, you execute
                "c:avail flush" but that will remove ALL unused libraries
                from memory, so the REMOVE switch gives you more control.

                I had plans for a FLUSH/S switch but decided not to implement
                it because it would be of little or no use in this program.
                Use "avail flush" or other programs to flush the memory.

@{b}WAIT/S@{ub}      :   LoadLibs will load the library/libraries and then WAITs for
                a break signal, in this case CTRL-C. It will then close
                the library/libraries and exit.

                This can be useful if you want to protect your
                library/libraries from being removed.

                @{b}To use this option in your s:user-startup or
                s:startup-sequence you need to RUN it!@{ub}

                @{i}run >nil: LoadLibs foo.library WAIT QUIET@{ui}

                To send a break signal you can use "LoadLibs BREAK" that
                will break @{b}all@{ub} instances of LoadLibs running or if you
                need more control you can use c:break or PriMan or any
                other program that can send signals to tasks.

@{b}BREAK/S@{ub}     :   Sends a break signal to all instances of LoadLibs.

                It actually sends a break signal to all programs with
                the same name as the name LoadLibs currently has.
                Confused? (I am:)

                What it means is that if you rename LoadLibs to LLibs
                and run "LLibs BREAK", LLibs (=LoadLibs) will break all
                programs with the name "LLibs" and totally ignore all
                programs with the name "LoadLibs".

@{b}VERSION/S@{ub}   :   Checks version number when opening the library/libraries.

                By default the version number checked is 0. The zero
                means that dos.library/OpenLibrary() will open any version
                of the specified library. If you really NEED a certain
                version LoadLibs will check the version and refuse to
                open the library if the version number is too low.
                It will also return WARN (5) to the CLI.

                The keyword "VERSION" or "V" is needed.

                @{i}1.0-> loadlibs icon.library VERSION 39
                LoadLibs 1.0 (5.9.97) ©1997 Mathias Karlsson
                icon.library v40.1 opened
                Closing icon.library

                1.0-> loadlibs icon.library V 42
                LoadLibs 1.0 (5.9.97) ©1997 Mathias Karlsson
                icon.library error!
                1.5->@{ui}

@{b}NOCLOSE/S@{ub}   :   LoadLibs doesn't close the library at exit.

                By not closing the library at exit it is protected from
                removal. It can no longer be removed by "avail flush" or
                "LoadLibs REMOVE" etc.

                In most cases the WAIT option is probably a better choice.

@{b}VERBOSE/S@{ub}   :   Print some extra information.

                In v1.0 of LoadLibs the extra information is limited to
                the IdString of the library when listing libraries.

                In the future more information will be printed both when
                listing libraries and when loading libraries.

               @{i} 1> LoadLibs LIST VERBOSE
                LoadLibs 1.0 (5.9.97) ©1997 Mathias Karlsson
                @{b}@{u}Library                VERSION OpenCnt Pri Address@{ub}@{uu}
                ixemul.library          45.1      0     0 $00054E58
                Id: ixemul 45.1 [68020, fpu] (1.1.97)@{ui}
                (...)

@{b}QUIET/S@{ub}     :   Will suppress output. All errors will still be printed.

                Should be used when you don't want any output, such as in
                the s:startup-sequence or s:user-startup. Errors will
                still be printed though, so if you really want LoadLibs to
                shut up you must redirect the output to nil:

               @{i} 13.0-> LoadLibs icon.library QUIET
                13.0-> LoadLibs gates.library QUIET
                gates.library error!
                13.5-> LoadLibs >nil: gates.library QUIET
                13.5->@{ui}
@endnode

@node "Tips&Tricks" "Tips&Tricks"
@{b}@{u}Using LoadLibs in s:startup-sequence and s:user-startup.@{ub}@{uu}

Using LoadLibs is easy, but when using it in the s:startup-sequence or
s:user-startup a few things could be worth to have in mind:

@{b}@{u}1.@{ub}@{uu} Always use it after you've made the necessary assigns. This may sound
obvious but some people are assigning LIBS: to many different directories and
those assigns are often made late.

@{b}@{u}2.@{ub}@{uu} Always use the QUIET/S switch when you use LoadLibs in the startup.
Otherwise the output from LoadLibs will make a window appear. If an error
occurs QUIET will be ignored and you will be notified what happened. If you
NEVER want any output you can redirect it to nil: using "LoadLibs >nil:
foo.library" but then you will _never_ get any error messages. Only redirect
to nil: if you know what your doing.

(in s:startup-sequence or s:user-startup)

    *   BAD         @{i}LoadLibs foo.library@{ui}
    *   GOOD       @{i} LoadLibs foo.library QUIET@{ui}
    *   EXPERT      @{i}LoadLibs >nil: foo.library@{ui}

@{b}@{u}3.@{ub}@{uu} If you are using the WAIT/S switch to prevent libraries from being flushed
out of the memory you must, of course, RUN LoadLibs.

    *   BAD         @{i}LoadLibs foo.library WAIT@{ui}
    *   GOOD        @{i}run >nil: LoadLibs foo.library WAIT@{ui}

However, to avoid unnecessary memory fragmentation the best usage of the
WAIT/S switch would be these to lines combined.

    @{i}LoadLibs foo.library QUIET
    run >nil: LoadLibs foo.library WAIT@{ui}

For more information on this read @{"4" link "Tips&Tricks" 37} and @{"5" link "Tips&Tricks" 70}.

@{b}@{u}4.@{ub}@{uu} When forcing libraries to be loaded to a specific memory block using the
TO/K option it could be wise not to have any other programs running at the
same time.

Why?

If the TO/K option is used LoadLibs gives the specified memory block the
highest possible priority and all memory allocations will end up there.
LoadLibs then loads all libraries to that memory and restores the original
priorities of the memory blocks.

If any other program tries to allocate memory at the same time they may
receive slower chipmem instead of the fastest possible memory.

LoadLibs temporarily changes its own priority to 2 to avoid this problem but
since the Amiga is multitasking this part of the startup may cause unwanted
results:

   @{i} run >nil: BigProgram
    LoadLibs foo.library TO chip#? QUIET@{ui}

You soon realize that BigProgram will run at the same time as LoadLibs and
BigProgram may allocate memory while LoadLibs has modified the priority of the
memory blocks.

The correct/best way is to switch the order of the two:

    [a few programs not started with 'run']
  @{i}  LoadLibs foo.library TO chip#? QUIET
    run >nil: BigProgram@{ui}

Since BigProgram is run after LoadLibs has finished the priorities are back to
normal.

@{b}@{u}5.@{ub}@{uu} Running LoadLibs with the WAIT/S and TO/S switches in combination. As
explained in @{"4" link "Tips&Tricks" 37} this may cause problem. One solution is to use NOCLOSE/S
instead of WAIT/S, by doing that you don't need to 'run' LoadLibs, another
solution is to do this:

  @{i}  LoadLibs foo.library TO chip#? QUIET
    run >nil: LoadLibs foo.library QUIET@{ui}

Since foo.library is already loaded into chip memory this will take almost no
time and use very little extra memory. It also results in less memory
fragmentation. I use this in my startup-sequence.

@{b}@{u}6.@{ub}@{uu} If you don't get the results you expected it may be because the library is
already opened by another program. Use this example to debug your use of
LoadLibs:

   @{i} LoadLibs >ram:before LIST
    LoadLibs >ram:liblist foo.library TO chip#? ;NOT QUIET!
    LoadLibs >ram:after LIST@{ui}

Then you can have a look at ram:before, ram:liblist and ram:after to see what
really happened.

@{b}@{u}7.@{ub}@{uu} In general, use LoadLibs as early as possible in the startup.
@endnode

